{[showcards N:D2]

You are East. The bidding has been as shown.

Partner led the \S6. You won the \SA and returned the \S9, won by South's \SQ.

South next played to dummy's \CA and led the \D2. What do you play?

Play the \DA.

Count the points. South's 15-17 plus North's 11 plus your 10 comes to 36-38. So West has room for an Ace or a King, but no more.

West's second \S play was the 2, so it looks like he started with 5 \Ss. And the fall of South's \Ss looks like he may have 1 \S left, very likely the \SK.

All this means that you should take your \DA now and return your last \S to establish West's suit. Now West's \DK will be an entry to the \Ss

If you play low, West will have to take the \DK now, and although he can play a \S to establish the suit, he will not have an entry to be able to cash them.}
[Play "W"]S6

